# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 3. HARDWARE SPECIFICATIONS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

SOLAR SENTINEL V1:
- MCU: ESP32-S3-WROOM-1 (dual-core 240MHz, WiFi + BLE)
- Secure element: ATECC608A (ECDSA P-256, I2C at 0x60)
- Primary meter: PZEM-017 DC (UART2: TX=GPIO17, RX=GPIO18)
- Backup sensor: INA226 (I2C) + ACS712 hall effect
- Radio: RFM95W LoRa 915MHz (SPI)
- Storage: 32GB MicroSD (SPI)
- Power: LM2596 buck 12-48V → 5V
- Enclosure: IP67 aluminum 100x68x50mm
- Telemetry interval: every 5 minutes
- BOM cost: $103.60 | Retail: $349 | Margin: 70.3%

HOME BIOREACTOR (BOKASHI KIT):
- MCU: ESP32-C3-MINI-1 (WiFi + BLE)
- Secure element: ATECC608A
- Weight: HX711 ADC + 10kg load cell
- Environmental: SHT40 temp/humidity (I2C)
- Gas: MQ-135 (NH3, CO2)
- Anti-counterfeit: SD card hash + challenge-response nonce
- Telemetry interval: every 1 hour
- BOM cost: $116.40 | Retail: $289 + $12/mo | Margin: 59.7%

PRO BIOREACTOR (INDUSTRIAL):
- MCU: Raspberry Pi Compute Module 4 (4GB RAM)
- Secure element: ATECC608A
- Weight: 4x 200kg load cells + HX711 (800kg total)
- Sensors: industrial pH probe, PT100 RTD, gas array (CH4/CO2/NH3/H2S)
- Connectivity: SIM7600 4G LTE + Ethernet
- Actuators: motorized auger + peristaltic pump
- Staking requirement: 10,000 SCARAB locked as SLA collateral
- BOM cost: $1,741.65 | Retail: $4,995 | Margin: 65.1%

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 4. SMART CONTRACT RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

When writing or editing Solidity:

ALWAYS:
- Use OpenZeppelin v5 contracts as base classes
- Include NatSpec comments on all public functions
- Use custom errors instead of require strings (gas efficiency)
- Emit events for every state change
- Use IS_TESTNET constructor flag for time-constraint bypassing
  Example: minCycleDuration = isTestnet ? 0 : 1 days;
- Store nonces as keccak256(deviceIdHash || nonce) for replay protection
- Use basis points (10000 = 100%) for percentage calculations

NEVER:
- Use tx.origin for authentication
- Use block.timestamp for randomness
- Write unbounded loops over storage arrays
- Use floating point — use fixed-point math (WAD = 1e18)
- Leave TODO comments in production code
- Use selfdestruct

SECURITY PATTERNS ALREADY IMPLEMENTED:
- Replay protection: mapping(bytes32 => bool) usedBranNonces
- Revenue splitter timelock: 30 days cooldown via scheduleTargetUpgrade()
- Device GPS locking: coordinates stored immutably at activation
- Activation burn: 50 SCARAB burned per device registration
- Oracle confidence: >=90% instant reward, 60-89% escrowed 24hr

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 5. BACKEND / ORACLE RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

When writing oracle_worker.js or any backend Node.js:

ARCHITECTURE:
- Devices POST signed telemetry to SQS queue
- Stateless workers pull from SQS (ReceiveMessageCommand)
- H3 level-5 hex cells for weather API spatial caching
- Redis for: idempotency locks, H3 weather cache, ASI-Evolve queue
- Batch up to 50 submissions per BSC transaction

IDEMPOTENCY PATTERN (always use this exact pattern):
  const isLocked = await redisClient.set(
    `lock:batch:${batchId}`,
    'processing',
    { NX: true, EX: 300 }  // 5-minute auto-expiry — CRITICAL
  );
  if (!isLocked) return; // already processing, skip

H3 WEATHER CACHE PATTERN:
  const h3Index = h3.latLngToCell(lat, lon, 5);
  const cacheKey = `weather:${h3Index}`;
  const cached = await redisClient.get(cacheKey);
  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached);
  // fetch from OpenWeatherMap API
  await redisClient.setEx(cacheKey, 300, JSON.stringify(data));

ASI-EVOLVE PIPELINE:
  // Push anomalies to training queue for model evolution
  await redisClient.lPush('asi_evolve:training_data', JSON.stringify({
    device_id, anomaly_type, raw_telemetry, timestamp
  }));

SIGNATURE VERIFICATION:
- Algorithm: ECDSA P-256 over SHA-256
- Signature: 64 bytes raw format, convert to DER before Node crypto
- Public key: registered in DeviceRegistry.sol at activation

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 6. FIRMWARE RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

When writing ESP32 firmware (Arduino/PlatformIO):

ALWAYS:
- Use PlatformIO, not Arduino IDE
- Handle WiFi disconnection gracefully — buffer to SD card
- Implement LoRa fallback after 3 consecutive WiFi failures
- Sign telemetry before transmission — never send unsigned data
- Use NTP time sync — reject submissions with timestamp drift > 60s
- Add watchdog timer (WDT) to recover from hangs

ATECC608A CRITICAL RULES:
- ECCX08.lock() is IRREVERSIBLE — only call in production provisioning
- Test configuration thoroughly before locking
- Private key slot 0 for device identity signing
- Always check Wire.begin() success before ECCX08.begin()
- Decoupling cap: 100nF X7R within 1mm of VCC pin

TELEMETRY PACKET STRUCTURE (always this exact field order for signing):
  {
    device_id, timestamp, voltage, current,
    power, energy, lat, lon
  }
  // Hash this with SHA-256, sign with ATECC608A slot 0
  // Then add: sig (base64), pubkey (hex)

PZEM-017 UART:
- ESP32 UART2: TX=GPIO17, RX=GPIO18
- Baud: 9600, 8N1
- Voltage divider on RX: 10kΩ + 20kΩ (5V → 3.3V)
- TX from ESP32 (3.3V) is compatible with PZEM 5V input directly

