- Activate venv before running: source scarab-agents/bin/activate

CONTENT RULES FOR SOCIAL GENERATOR:
- Never write price predictions
- Never write financial advice
- Never use "moon", "pump", "100x" or similar language
- Always educational tone
- Always end Twitter posts with scarabprotocol.org

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 8. SECURITY & IP PROTECTION RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

NEVER suggest or write code that:
- Puts API keys, private keys, or secrets in source code
- Commits .env files (always in .gitignore)
- Exposes BOM costs, component margins, or manufacturing details
  in any frontend or public-facing code
- Shares GPS coordinates of individual devices in data market output
  (aggregate only — minimum 10 devices per data point)
- Reveals the ATECC608A signing key generation process in public docs

ALWAYS remind me to:
- Use GitHub Secrets for all CI/CD credentials
- Keep .env in .gitignore
- Use IS_TESTNET flag instead of commenting out security constraints

IP STATUS:
- Provisional patent: NOT YET FILED (file before posting hardware diagrams)
- Trademark: NOT YET FILED (file before social media launch)
- Until filed: never generate or display circuit diagrams, PCB layouts,
  or detailed BOM in any public-facing file

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 9. CODE QUALITY STANDARDS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

General rules for ALL code in this project:

- Production-grade only — no tutorial shortcuts
- Every function needs a one-line comment explaining WHY not WHAT
- Error handling is mandatory — no silent failures
- Log levels: ERROR for failures, INFO for state changes, DEBUG for data
- Test files go in /test directory, named *.test.ts or test_*.py
- Gas optimization matters in Solidity — measure before and after changes
- TypeScript preferred over JavaScript for new backend files
- Python type hints required on all function signatures

WHEN YOU SPOT A BUG:
- Flag it immediately before suggesting any new code
- State the severity: CRITICAL / HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW
- Explain the exploit scenario for security bugs
- Provide the fix, not just the diagnosis

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# 10. RESPONSE STYLE IN CURSOR
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- Be direct — I am on a student budget and limited credits
- No filler phrases ("Certainly!", "Great question!", "Of course!")
- When editing code, show only the changed lines plus 3 lines context
- When explaining architecture, use bullet points not paragraphs
- Flag any assumption you make with [ASSUMPTION: ...]
- If a task needs clarification, ask ONE question only
- Always state the cost implication of any paid API or service suggestion
- Prefer free/open-source solutions unless paid is clearly worth it

